The therapatch device is a two-part build, with an external battery case carried in your pocket and the main heating/cooling unit

The main unit consists of a 70x70x45mm body with 3mm walls and M2 screw holes
The heating and cooling unit (peliter) sits in a 41x41 cutout, above it, dissipating its heat and cold is the heat sink, and above the heat sink is the fan, both of which are 60x60mm 
The cutouts (USB-C barrel jack, LCD window, and button holes) all line up with the board's connectors
The lid locks the internal components within the case, with M2 self-tapping screws (1.6mm holes on the case, 2.2mm holes on the lid)

The battery caddy is  81x67x29mm with 2.5mm walls
Its main purpose is to hold the 3S batteries, it has a screw-on lid, and the wire passes out of a slit on the lid
kept separate so the main unit isn't overly bulky and maximizes comfort for users.

All parts were designed in Onshape with STL and STEP files in "CADfiles"
